{"author":{"id":"222a064dabc38896d34e2f40eca4106beb1a3fa7dfe16ff52f0598bf0153ef39"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1594207985,"nonce":"TY1YxMESlvgxc4rvHGyfdPPY1Os=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY1NTQ2MTkwMw==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/3111#issuecomment-655461903"},"message":"Yes actually, I had noticed the same thing and was composing a similar issue regarding the xml/json issue (among other issues like not being able to generate a list of IDs from the search that could be provided to efetch's ID list input, or being able to view the results (in 20.01 - fixed in 20.05)), but before submitting, I tried testing and ran into this issue.  I have a number of observations about the tools that I would like to look into.","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1594847017,"nonce":"z7MUh6dDxzOMEY3zfuk5FU1YHec=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDY1OTAwODk1MA==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/3111#issuecomment-659008950"},"message":"OK. I just read through the other issue after figuring things out a bit WRT the galaxy tool wrapper for Entrez eutils. I have confirmed that Biopython's `Entrez.efetch()` method will never work when supplied a history as a source for IDs to retrieve records for.  The eutils NCBI API can utilize a history as the ID source, but the biopython code never attempts to use it.  It only takes a list of IDs (either by file or as a string).  I wrote a quick one-off version of the galaxy wrapper's efetch.py which circumvents the biopython efetch method and directly calls it's private `_open()` method (supplying it the webenv string and query_key), and it works.  I'm manually able to supply a `webenv` and `query_key` value and retrieve fasta records.\n\nI also updated `elink.{py,xml}` in the galaxy wrapper to make it work and added `linkname` and `retmode` parameters so I could better control the types of IDs I got back and could change the type to json.  However, 